han Britain itself, forcing the nation to become more dependent on global resources. Otter shows how this issue expands beyond Britain, looking at the global effects of large agro-food systems that require more resources than our planet can sustain. This comprehensive history helps us understand how the British played a significant role in making red meat, white bread, and sugar the diet of choice—linked to wealth, luxury, and power—and shows how dietary choices connect to the pressing issues of climate change and food supply.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDietzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aDietzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aFood consumptionzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aFood supplyzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aHuman ecologyxHistory. 0aHuman ecologyzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aNutritionzGreat BritainxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBritish diet.  aecological footprint.  afood systems.  afood.  ameat.  anutrition transition.  asugar.  awheat.  aworld ecology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831106930960 cprintz978022669710940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226705965423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226705965/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 